
=====================================================
EXECUTORSERVICE.submit() – ALL OVERLOADS (COMPLETE NOTES)
=====================================================

ExecutorService provides THREE submit() methods.

-----------------------------------------------------
1) submit(Runnable task)
-----------------------------------------------------

Method signature:
Future<?> submit(Runnable task);

Key points:
- Runnable does NOT return any value.
- submit() still returns a Future object.
- Future.get() will return null on successful completion.
- If Runnable throws an exception, get() throws ExecutionException.

Sample:
----------------------------------
Future<?> future = executorService.submit(
        () -> System.out.println("Runnable executed")
);

System.out.println(future.get()); // Output: null
----------------------------------


-----------------------------------------------------
2) submit(Runnable task, T result)
-----------------------------------------------------

Method signature:
<T> Future<T> submit(Runnable task, T result);

Key points:
- Runnable still does NOT return anything.
- You manually provide a result to be returned.
- If Runnable completes successfully:
    → Future.get() returns the provided result.
- If Runnable throws an exception:
    → Future.get() throws ExecutionException.

Why this exists:
- Useful when you want:
  "Task completed successfully" message
  or a predefined status/result.

Sample:
----------------------------------
Future<String> future = executorService.submit(
        () -> System.out.println("Runnable executed"),
        "SUCCESS"
);

System.out.println(future.get()); // Output: SUCCESS
----------------------------------


-----------------------------------------------------
3) submit(Callable<T> task)
-----------------------------------------------------

Method signature:
<T> Future<T> submit(Callable<T> task);

Key points:
- Callable CAN return a value.
- Callable CAN throw checked exceptions.
- Future.get() returns the computed value.
- Preferred when result is required.

Sample:
----------------------------------
Future<Integer> future = executorService.submit(
        () -> 42
);

System.out.println(future.get()); // Output: 42
----------------------------------


-----------------------------------------------------
Runnable vs Callable – Quick Comparison
-----------------------------------------------------

Runnable:
- Method: void run()
- No return value
- Cannot throw checked exceptions
- Future.get() → null (unless result is supplied manually)

Callable:
- Method: V call() throws Exception
- Returns a value
- Can throw checked exceptions
- Future.get() → returned value


-----------------------------------------------------
Common Mistakes
-----------------------------------------------------

❌ Runnable returning value:
Runnable r = () -> "Hello";   // INVALID

❌ Assigning Runnable submit to Future<String>:
Future<String> f = executorService.submit(
        () -> System.out.println("Hello")
); // INVALID

✅ Correct:
Future<?> f = executorService.submit(
        () -> System.out.println("Hello")
);

Minimal Working Demo (Optional)

ExecutorService executorService = Executors.newSingleThreadExecutor();

Future<?> f1 = executorService.submit(() -> System.out.println("Runnable"));
Future<String> f2 = executorService.submit(() -> System.out.println("Runnable"), "DONE");
Future<Integer> f3 = executorService.submit(() -> 100);

System.out.println(f1.get()); // null
System.out.println(f2.get()); // DONE
System.out.println(f3.get()); // 100

executorService.shutdown(
-----------------------------------------------------
INTERVIEW ONE-LINER SUMMARY
-----------------------------------------------------

- submit(Runnable) → Future<?> → get() returns null
- submit(Runnable, result) → Future<T> → get() returns provided result
- submit(Callable<T>) → Future<T> → get() returns computed value
- Callable is preferred when result or checked exceptions are needed

