-----------------PART 2 NOTES:- -------------------

/*
=====================================================
EXECUTORSERVICE – LIFECYCLE & CONTROL METHODS (NOTES)
=====================================================

ExecutorService controls the lifecycle of thread pools.
Below are the MOST IMPORTANT methods used in real projects
and frequently asked in interviews.

-----------------------------------------------------
1) shutdown()
-----------------------------------------------------

Method:
void shutdown();

What it does:
- Stops accepting NEW tasks.
- Already submitted tasks WILL continue to execute.
- Does NOT block the calling thread.

Important:
- shutdown() does NOT wait for tasks to finish.
- After shutdown(), isShutdown() returns true.
- Executor fully terminates only after all tasks finish.

Example:
----------------------------------
executorService.shutdown();
----------------------------------


-----------------------------------------------------
2) shutdownNow()
-----------------------------------------------------

Method:
List<Runnable> shutdownNow();

What it does:
- Attempts to stop ALL running tasks immediately.
- Interrupts running threads.
- Returns a list of tasks that were submitted but NOT started.

Important:
- No guarantee tasks will stop (depends on interruption handling).
- Threads must check interruption status.

Example:
----------------------------------
List<Runnable> pendingTasks = executorService.shutdownNow();
----------------------------------


-----------------------------------------------------
3) isShutdown()
-----------------------------------------------------

Method:
boolean isShutdown();

What it checks:
- Returns true if shutdown() or shutdownNow() has been called.
- Does NOT indicate whether tasks have finished.

Example:
----------------------------------
if (executorService.isShutdown()) {
    System.out.println("Executor is shut down");
}
----------------------------------


-----------------------------------------------------
4) isTerminated()
-----------------------------------------------------

Method:
boolean isTerminated();

What it checks:
- Returns true ONLY when:
  a) shutdown() or shutdownNow() is called AND
  b) ALL tasks have completed AND
  c) ALL threads have stopped

Important:
- isTerminated() can return false even after shutdown().

Example:
----------------------------------
if (executorService.isTerminated()) {
    System.out.println("Executor fully terminated");
}
----------------------------------


-----------------------------------------------------
5) awaitTermination(timeout, unit)
-----------------------------------------------------

Method:
boolean awaitTermination(long timeout, TimeUnit unit)
        throws InterruptedException;

What it does:
- Blocks the calling thread for the given time.
- Waits for executor to fully terminate.

Return value:
- true  → executor terminated within timeout
- false → timeout elapsed before termination

Example:
----------------------------------
executorService.shutdown();
if (!executorService.awaitTermination(5, TimeUnit.SECONDS)) {
    executorService.shutdownNow();
}
----------------------------------


-----------------------------------------------------
6) submit() vs shutdown() relationship
-----------------------------------------------------

- submit() → adds tasks to executor queue.
- shutdown() → stops accepting new tasks.
- shutdownNow() → interrupts running tasks.
- isShutdown() → checks shutdown request.
- isTerminated() → checks actual termination.

Execution Flow (Typical):
----------------------------------
submit tasks
shutdown()
awaitTermination()
shutdownNow() (if needed)
----------------------------------


-----------------------------------------------------
INTERVIEW ONE-LINER SUMMARY
-----------------------------------------------------

- shutdown() stops accepting new tasks but lets existing tasks finish
- shutdownNow() attempts to stop everything immediately
- isShutdown() checks whether shutdown was requested
- isTerminated() checks whether executor has fully stopped
- awaitTermination() waits for termination with timeout

=====================================================
*/
